TITLE:
	Proof by weakened induction hypothesis

AUTHOR:
	Eric Johannesson,
	eric.johannesson@philosophy.su.se

AUTHOR:
	Anders Lundstedt,
	anders.lundstedt@philosophy.su.se


ABSTRACT:
	Sometimes, in order to a prove an arithmetical fact ∀xφ(x) by
	induction, straightforward induction “does not work”. Instead one
	“must” use a “stronger” induction hypothesis ψ(x) and prove ∀xψ(x),
	from which ∀xφ(x) may be derived. This is sometimes
	called “proof by strengthened induction hypothesis”.
	We show that this is an instance of a more general phenomenon
	which we call *proof by non-straightforward induction*.
	Cruacially, we show that there are cases
	where straightforward induction fails, but where proof by
	*incomparable* or even *weaker* induction hypothesis succeeds.


§	SEC:intro
Introduction

¶

Sometimes, in order to a prove an arithmetical fact ∀xφ(x) by induction,
straightforward induction “does not work”. Instead one “must” use a
“stronger” induction hypothesis ψ(x) and prove ∀xψ(x), from which ∀xφ(x)
may be derived. This is sometimes called “proof by
strengthened induction hypothesis”.

¶

To give an example, suppose we want to prove that, for all natural numbers
n, the sum of the first n odd numbers is a perfect square. Straightforward
induction yields the following:

-	Base case: the sum of the first 0 odd numbers is 0, which is a
	perfect square.

-	Inductive step: if the sum of the first n odd numbers is a perfect
	square k², then the sum of the first n + 1 odd numbers is

		1 + 3 + ... + (2n - 1) + (2n + 1) = k² + 2n + 1

	But it is not true that k² + 2n + 1 is a perfect square for all k
	and n. So we are “stuck”.

¶

Instead, we may prove the following *more general* or *stronger* result by
induction:
for all natural numbers n, the sum of the first n odd numbers is n².
Straightforward induction yields the following:

-	Base case: the sum of the 0 first odd numbers is 0, which is 0².

-	Inductive step: if the sum of the first n odd numbers is n², then
	the sum of the first n + 1 odd numbers is n² + 2n + 1 = (n + 1)².



§	SEC:precise
Making it precise

¶

What does it mean, more precisely, to say that straightforward induction
to prove ∀xφ(x) “does not work”, and that we “must” use a “stronger”
induction hypothesis and first prove ∀xψ(x)?

Here is how *not* to characterize the situation (where PA is Peano
arithmetic):

()	PA ⊬ φ(0) ∧ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x'))	DSP:bad1
()	PA ⊢ ψ(0) ∧ ∀x(ψ(x) → ψ(x'))	DSP:bad2
()	PA ⊢ ∀xψ(x) → ∀xφ(x)		DSP:bad3

In fact, this situation is impossible: [DSP:bad2] yields PA ⊢ ∀xψ(x),
which by [DSP:bad3] yields PA ⊢ ∀xφ(x), which by pure logic yields

	PA ⊢ φ(0) ∧ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x'))

which contradicts [DSP:bad1].

¶

Instead, the situation may perhaps be characterized as follows: starting
from the axioms of Peano arithmetic minus the induction axioms, we
successively prove more and more theorems using logic and the rule of
induction:

	φ(0)   ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x'))
	───────────────────────
	         ∀xφ(x)

Suppose that, at some stage in this process of mathematical inquiry, we
have reached a theory T consisting of the axioms and hitherto proved
theorems.
Then, as we show in [SEC:model] below, a situation may indeed
arise satisfying the following definition:

¶	DEF:good
Proof by non-straightforward induction

We say that a theory T and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x) exemplify a case of
*proof by non-straightforward induction* just in case

()	T ⊬ φ(0) ∧ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x'))	DSP:good1
()	T ⊢ ψ(0) ∧ ∀x(ψ(x) → ψ(x'))	DSP:good2
()	T ⊢ ∀xψ(x) → ∀xφ(x)		DSP:good3

¶	FCT:good

There are extensions T of Robinson arithmetic and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x)
exemplifying cases of proof by non-straightforward induction.

¶

Perhaps more surprisingly, proof by non-straightforward induction
does not really require ψ(x) to be *stronger* than φ(x).
As we show in [SEC:weaker] below, there are cases of proof by
non-straightforward induction where,
relative to T, ψ(x) is actually *weaker* than φ(x).

§	SEC:model
A non-standard model

¶

We define a non-standard model M of Robinson arithmetic as follows.
Let

	A = {..., a[−2], a[−1], a[0] ,a[1] , a[2], ...}

be a countably infinite set disjoint from the natural numbers ℕ, and let
the domain of the model be ℕ ∪ A.
We shall call A the (set of) *non-standard numbers* (of M).
Let the constant 0 be interpreted as the number 0, and extend the
interpretation of the function symbols ', +, and × to the non-standard
numbers as follows:

()	a[z]' = a[z+1] for z ∈ ℤ.				DSP:m1

()	a[z] + n = n + a[z] = a[z+n] for z ∈ ℤ and n ∈ ℕ.	DSP:m2

()	a[z] + a[u] = a[u] + a[z] = a[z+u] for z,u ∈ ℤ.		DSP:m3

()	a[z] × 0 = 0 × a[z] = 0 for z ∈ ℤ.			DSP:m4

()	a[z] × n = n × a[z] = a[z × n] for z ∈ ℤ and n ∈ ℕ − {0}.	DSP:m5

()	a[z] × a[u] = a[u] × a[z] = a[z × u] for z,u ∈ ℤ.	DSP:m6

¶

It can easily be verified that M is also a model of what we may call 
*minimal arithmetic*, which is the theory you get by adding commutativity,
associativity and distribution laws for addition and multiplication to the
axioms of Robinson arithmetic.

¶	PRF
of [FCT:good]

To verify that cases of proof by non-straightforward induction are indeed
possible, it
suffices to find *true* formulas φ(x) and ψ(x) (*true* in the sense of
being satisfied by all natural numbers in the standard model as well as in
the non-standard model) with the following profile regarding the
non-standard numbers of M:

	       ...  a[−2]  a[−1]  a[0]   a[1]   a[2]   ...
	     ──────────────────────────────────────────────
	φ(x) | ...  false  false  true   false  false  ...
	ψ(x) | ...  false  false  false  false  false  ...

The induction step will then fail for φ(x) with a[0] assigned to x, but
will not fail for ψ(x).
Granted as much, we can let T be the theory you get by adding, to minimal
arithmetic, the axioms

()	ψ(0) ∧ ∀x(ψ(x) → ψ(x'))		DSP:ind
()	∀xψ(x) → ∀xφ(x)			DSP:imp

Since [DSP:ind] and [DSP:imp] will be true in M, the model will satisfy T.
Moreover, [DSP:good1] will be satisfied as witnessed by a[0] assigned to x.

For instance, let φ(x) be the formula

	∀y∀z(x = x × x ∨ (y + x = z + x → y = z))

and let ψ(x) be the formula

	∀y∀z(y + x = z + x → y = z)

Clearly, ψ(x) characterizes the non-standard numbers of M in the sense that
they and only they fail to satisfy it. But due to [DSP:m5],
φ(x) is satisfied by M in the special case of a[0] being assigned to x.

§	SEC:weaker
Proof by non-strengthened induction hypothesis

¶

In the proof of [FCT:good], ψ(x) was *stronger* than φ(x), even in the 
sense that ⊢ ∀x(ψ(x) → φ(x)). Thus, this was a clear case of *proof by
strengthened induction hypothesis*, albeit a contrived one.

But does *proof by non-straightforward induction* really require a 
stronger induction hypothesis?
No. As a matter of fact, there are cases of what we call
*proof by incomparable induction hypothesis* and
*proof by weakened induction hypothesis*, respectively.


¶	DEF:inc
Proof by incomparable induction hypothesis

We say that a theory T and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x) exemplify a case of
*proof by incomparable induction hypothesis* just in case they exemplify
a case of proof by non-straightforward induction and, in addition,

()	T ⊢ ∀xφ(x) → ∀xψ(x)	DSP:inc1
()	T ⊬ ∀x(ψ(x) → φ(x))	DSP:inc2
()	T ⊬ ∀x(φ(x) → ψ(x))	DSP:inc3

¶	RMK

By [DSP:inc1] and [DSP:good3], we have in effect

	T ⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ ∀xψ(x)

But because of [DSP:inc2] and [DSP:inc3], we may still say that φ(x) and 
ψ(x) are *incomparable* relative to T.

¶	FCT:inc

There are extensions T of Robinson arithmetic and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x)
exemplifying a case of proof by incomparable induction hypothesis.

¶	PRF:inc

To show that proof by incomparable induction hypothesis is possible,
it suffices to find true formulas
φ(x) and ψ(x) with the following profile regarding the non-standard
numbers of M:

	       ...  a[−2]  a[−1]  a[0]   a[1]   a[2]   ...
	     ──────────────────────────────────────────────
	φ(x) | ...  true   true   true   false  false  ...
	ψ(x) | ...  false  false  true   true   true   ...

For instance, let φ(x) be the formula

	∀y(x ≠ y ∧ ∃z(y + z = x) → x × x ≠ y × y)

and let ψ(x) be the formula

	∀y(x ≠ y ∧ ∃z(x + z = y) → x × x ≠ y × y)

Observe that, by simple relabeling of variables, we have

()	⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ ∀xψ(x)

Thus, let T be the theory you get by adding, to minimal arithmetic,
the axiom

()	ψ(0) ∧ ∀x(ψ(x) → ψ(x'))

Clearly, both φ(x) and ψ(x) are true of all natural numbers in the
standard model.
To verify that φ(x) has the required profile with respect to M,
we need to consider the following two cases:

-	x is assigned a natural number n. Whatever y is assigned that is
	distinct from n, it will
	be true in M that x × x ≠ y × y. So φ(x) is true of the natural
	numbers of M.

-	x is assigned a non-standard number a[i] for some integer i.
	Then either y is assigned a natural number, in which case M
	satisfies the antecedent x × x ≠ y × y, or y is assigned a
	non-standard number
	a[j] for some integer j ≠ i. By [DSP:m6], whenever j < i < 1, M
	satisfies x × x ≠ y × y. Likewise, whenever i > 0 and j = -i, M
	satisfies ∃z(y + z = x) and x × x = y × y. Thus, φ(x) is true
	in M for every non-standard number a[i] such that i < 1, and
	false whenever i > 0.

By symmetry of reasoning, we see that ψ(x) also has the required profile.

¶	DEF:weak
Proof by weakened induction hypothesis

We say that a theory T and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x) exemplify a case of
*proof by weakened induction hypothesis* just in case they they exemplify
a case of proof by non-straightforward induction and, in addition,

()	T ⊢ ∀xφ(x) → ∀xψ(x)	DSP:weak1
()	T ⊬ ∀x(ψ(x) → φ(x))	DSP:weak2
()	T ⊢ ∀x(φ(x) → ψ(x))	DSP:weak3


¶	RMK

By [DSP:weak1] and [DSP:good3], we have in effect

	T ⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ ∀xψ(x)

But because of [DSP:weak2] and [DSP:weak3], we may still say that ψ(x)
is *weaker* than φ(x) relative to T.

¶	FCT:weak

There are extensions T of Robinson arithmetic and formulas φ(x) and ψ(x)
exemplifying a case of proof by weakened induction hypothesis.



¶	PRF

To show that proof by weakened induction hypothesis is possible,
it suffices to find true 
formulas φ(x) and ψ(x) with the following profile:

	       ...  a[−2]  a[−1]  a[0]   a[1]   a[2]   ...
	     ──────────────────────────────────────────────
	φ(x) | ...  false  false  true   false  false  ...
	ψ(x) | ...  false  false  true   true   true   ...

For instance, let φ(x) be the formula

	∀y(x ≠ y → x × x ≠ y × y)

and let ψ(x) be the formula

	∀y(x ≠ y ∧ ∃z(x + z = y) → x × x ≠ y × y)

Observe that ⊢ ∀x(φ(x) → ψ(x)). It should be clear from [PRF:inc] that the
formulas have the required profile.
Moreover, with u < v defined as

	u ≠ v ∧ ∃z(u + z = v)

we have

()	∀x∀y(x < y ∨ x = y ∨ y < x) ⊢ ∀xψ(x) → ∀xφ(x)

To see why, assume that

()	∀x∀y(x < y ∨ x = y ∨ y < x)	DSP:tot

and

()	∀x∀y(x ≠ y ∧ ∃z(x + z = y) → x × x ≠ y × y)	DSP:psi

Suppose that x ≠ y. By [DSP:tot], we have x < y or y < x.
In the case of x < y, we have by definition that ∃z(x + z = y). Thus, by
[DSP:psi], we have x × x ≠ y × y, as desired.
In the case of y < x, we have by definition that ∃z(y + z = x).
By [DSP:tot], we get by relabeling of variables that

	∀y∀x(y ≠ x ∧ ∃z(y + z = x) → y × y ≠ x × x)

Hence, by [DSP:psi], we get y × y ≠ x × x, which yields the desired result
by pure logic.

Lastly, we observe that M satisfies [DSP:tot].
Thus, let T be the theory you get by adding, to minimal arithmetic, the axioms

()	∀x∀y(x < y ∨ x = y ∨ y < x)
()	ψ(0) ∧ ∀x(ψ(x) → ψ(x'))

¶	RMK

We here have cases where, relative to a base theory T, one *must* use a
different induction hypothesis, and *may* use one that is not stronger.
Are there cases where one both *may* and *must* use a non-strengthened
induction hypothesis? Indeed there are! ([FCT:fct2]).
This follows from a result reported by Hetzl and Wong
in [ITM:Hetzl&Wong], which we expand upon below.



§	SEC:gen
Proof by necessarily non-strengthened induction hypothesis

¶

It can be shown that, if something is provable in an arithmetical theory containing all the
induction axioms, it is provable in that theory using at most one induction axiom.
This generalizes Corollary 2.10 reported by Hetzl and Wong.


¶	DEF:indax

For each formula Θ(x,z̄), we define the corresponding induction axiom IΘ as the closed formula

	∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → ∀xθ(x,z̄)]

¶	LMA:lma
Generalizing Lemma 2.8 of Hetzl and Wong

Let Θ(x,z̄) be a formula, and define φ(x) as

	∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → θ(x,z̄)]

Then we have

()	⊢ φ(0) ∧ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x')) 	LMA:lma1

and

()	⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ Iθ			LMA:lma2


¶	PRF

First we show [LMA:lma1]. We have φ(0) by ∧-elimination, →-introduction and ∀-introduction. To show the
second conjunct, assume φ(a), i.e.

()	∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → θ(a,z̄)]	DSP:lma1ass1

Assume also 

()	θ(0, b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y, b̄) → θ(y',b̄))		DSP:lma1ass2

By [DSP:lma1ass1] and ∀-elimination, we have

	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄)) → θ(a,b̄)

With [DSP:lma1ass2], →-elimination yields Θ(a,b̄). By the second
conjunct of [DSP:lma1ass2], this yields Θ(a',b̄).
Discharing [DSP:lma1ass2], →-introduction yields

	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄)) → θ(a',b̄)

By ∀-introduction, we get

	∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → θ(a',z̄)]

Discharging [DSP:lma1ass1], →-introduction yields ⊢ φ(a) → φ(a'), and
∀-introduction finally yields ⊢ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x')).

Secondly, we show [LMA:lma2]. For right to left, assume Iθ, i.e.

()	∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → ∀xθ(x,z̄)]	DSP:lma2ass1

We need to show ∀xφ(x), i.e.

()	∀x∀z̄[θ(0,z̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,z̄) → θ(y',z̄)) → θ(x,z̄)]	DSP:lma2goal

To this end, assume

()	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄))			DSP:lma2ass2

By [DSP:lma2ass1] and ∀-elimination, we get

	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄)) → ∀xθ(x,b̄)

With [DSP:lma2ass2], →-elimination yields ∀xθ(x,b̄), which
by ∀-elimination yields θ(a,b̄). Discharging [DSP:lma2ass2],
→-introduction followed by ∀-introduction yields [DSP:lma2goal].

For left to right, assume [DSP:lma2goal]. We need to show [DSP:lma2ass1].
To this end, assume

()	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄))		DSP:lma2ass3

By [DSP:lma2goal] and ∀-elimination, we get

	θ(0,b̄) ∧ ∀y(θ(y,b̄) → θ(y',b̄)) → θ(a,b̄)

Together with [DSP:lma2ass3] and →-elimination, this yields get θ(a,b̄).
By ∀-introduction, this yields ∀xΘ(x,b̄). Discharging [DSP:lma2ass3],
→-introduction followed by ∀-introduction yields [DSP:lma2ass1].


¶	FCT:fct1
Generalizing Proposition 2.9 of Hetzl and Wong

For any formulas θ₁(x,z̄), ..., θₙ(x,z̄), there is a formula φ(x) such
that

()	⊢ ϕ(0) ∧ ∀x(ϕ(x) → ϕ(x'))	DSP:fct1.1

and

()	⊢ ∀xϕ(x) ↔ Iθ₁ ∧ ... ∧ Iθₙ	DSP:fct1.2

¶	PRF:prf1

By [LMA:lma], there is a formula φₖ(x) for each 1 ≤ k ≤ n such that

()	⊢ φₖ(0) ∧ ∀x(φₖ(x) → φₖ(x'))	DSP:prf1.1

and

()	⊢ ∀xφₖ(x) ↔ Iθₖ			DSP:prf1.2

Define φ(x) as φ₁(x) ∧ ... ∧ φₙ(x). Then [DSP:fct1.1] easily follows from
[DSP:prf1.1]. Likewise, [DSP:fct1.2] follows from [DSP:prf1.2] and the fact
that

	⊢ ∀xφ₁(x) ∧ ... ∧ ∀xφₙ(x) ↔ ∀x(φ₁(x) ∧ ... ∧ φₙ(x))

¶	FCT:crl1

For any formulas θ₁(x,z̄), ..., θₙ(x,z̄), there is a formula φ(x)
such that ⊢ Iφ ↔ Iθ₁ ∧ ... ∧ Iθₙ.

¶	PRF

By [FCT:fct1], there is a formula φ(x) such that

	⊢ φ(0) ∧ ∀x(φ(x) → φ(x'))

and

	⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ Iθ₁ ∧ ... ∧ Iθₙ

What remains is to observe that ⊢ ∀xφ(x) ↔ Iφ. Left to right follows essentially
by ∀-elimination. For right to left, assume Iφ. Then ∀xφ(x)
follows by →-elimination.

¶	FCT:crl2
Generalizing Corollary 2.10 of Hetzl and Wong

Let IND be the set of induction axioms, let T be a set of sentences,
and let σ be a sentence. If T + IND ⊢ σ, then there is a formula φ(x) such
that T + Iφ ⊢ σ.

¶	PRF

Assume that T + IND ⊢ σ. Then there is a finite set
θ₁(x,z̄), ..., θₙ(x,z̄) of formulas such that T + Iθ₁ + ... + Iθₙ ⊢ σ.
By [FCT:crl1], there is a formula φ(x) such that 
⊢ Iφ ↔ Iθ₁ ∧ ... ∧ Iθₙ. Hence, T + Iφ ⊢ σ.

¶	FCT:fct2
Generalizing Proposition 3.2 of Hetzl and Wong

Assume that T + IND ⊢ σ but T ⊬ σ, and let φ(x) be x = 0 → σ.
Then we have

()	T + IND ⊢ ∀xφ(x)	DSP:fct2.1
()	T ⊬ ∀xφ(x)		DSP:fct2.2

and there is ψ(x) such that

()	T + Iψ ⊢ ∀xφ(x)		DSP:fct2.3

Moreover, for any such ψ(x), we have 

()	T ⊬ ∀x(ψ(x) → φ(x))	DSP:fct2.4

¶	PRF

The first part follows by [FCT:crl2]. For the last part, assume that ψ(x) is a
formula of the required kind. Since T ⊬ σ, there is a model M of T such
that M ⊭ σ and thus M ⊭ ∀xφ(x). Hence, by [DSP:fct2.3], we have M ⊭ Iψ,
which means that M ⊨ ψ(0) but M ⊭ φ(0). Hence, M ⊭ ψ(0) → ϕ(0),
so T ⊬ ∀x(ψ(x) → φ(x)).

¶	RMK

The authors are not aware of any “natural” cases of proof by incomparable
or weakened induction hypothesis.
Observe that [FCT:fct2] does not yield a case where
straightforward induction fails in the induction step, since
T ⊬ ϕ(0) but T ⊢ ∀x(ϕ(x) → ϕ(x')).

§ REFS

[]	ITM:Hetzl&Wong
	Hetzl, S. and Wong, T. L. (2018). Some observations on the logical
	foundations of inductive theorem proving. Logical Methods in
	Computer Science, Volume 13, Issue 4.
